\section{Introduction}
Autonomous navigation of marine vessels has witnessed significant progress in recent years, driven by advances in control theory, sensor fusion, and data-driven decision-making~\cite{}--\cite{}. This is reflected in the growing deployment of unmanned surface vehicles (USVs) for applications ranging from ocean surveying and environmental monitoring to maritime search and rescue and autonomous cargo transport. Despite these developments, achieving robust autonomy in open and confined waterways remains a challenging problem, particularly in the presence of environmental disturbances such as wind, waves, and ocean currents. A foundational requirement for any autonomous marine system is an accurate kinematic model of the vessel, as high-level planning, motion prediction, and feedback control all depend critically on the fidelity of this underlying representation.

Marine vessels are commonly described by a variety of motion models, 
including the Unicycle model, the Bicycle Kinematic 
model~\cite{campion1996structural}, the Three-DOF Ship 
model~\cite{fossen2011handbook}, and the Nomoto model~\cite{nomoto1957}, 
each capturing different aspects of the vessel's translational and 
rotational dynamics. The choice of motion model directly influences the 
accuracy of trajectory prediction and the stability of control 
actions. In practice, however, the true governing 
model of a deployed vessel is rarely known a priori, as it depends on 
hull geometry, propulsion configuration, loading conditions, and 
hydrodynamic parameters that are difficult to measure 
directly~\cite{xue2021greybox}. This creates a fundamental model 
uncertainty problem: autonomous systems must operate under assumptions 
about vessel dynamics that may not hold across different vessels or 
operating conditions.

Existing approaches to motion model identification typically rely on 
dedicated sensing modalities, white-box system identification procedures, 
or explicit access to control inputs and onboard inertial measurements~\cite{}. Physics-based identification methods 
require extensive hydrodynamic testing and model-specific parameter 
fitting, which limits their generalizability across vessel 
types~\cite{}. Sensor-based approaches using IMUs, GPS, or 
force measurement systems improve estimation accuracy but introduce 
dependencies on hardware configurations that may not be available in all 
operational contexts~\cite{}. Crucially, the majority 
of these methods treat motion model identification as a regression or 
parameter estimation problem~\cite{brunton2016sindy}, rather than as a 
classification task that can be solved directly from observed trajectory 
data alone~\cite{sebastian2019terrain}.

In this work, we propose a data-driven framework for ego ship motion 
model classification that operates exclusively on the observed pose 
trajectory of the vessel, without requiring access to explicit control 
inputs, onboard sensor measurements, or model-specific parameter 
knowledge. From the raw pose sequence, a set of dynamics-oriented 
kinematic features is derived, including surge and sway velocities, yaw 
rate, yaw acceleration, and path curvature, which encode the intrinsic 
dynamic characteristics of each motion model while remaining invariant to 
global coordinate frames and operator-specific maneuver styles. These 
features are processed by a Temporal Convolutional Network (TCN) 
encoder~\cite{bai2018empirical} trained under a joint objective combining 
supervised contrastive loss~\cite{khosla2020supervised} and cross-entropy 
loss. The contrastive component enforces intra-class compactness and 
inter-class separation in the embedding space, while the cross-entropy 
component directly optimizes class discrimination, enabling the model to 
generalize across diverse maneuver profiles rather than overfitting to 
trajectory-specific artifacts.

The proposed method avoids dependence on image-based or vision-derived inputs, which are susceptible to degradation under adverse maritime conditions such as fog, glare, and low visibility. Instead, classification is performed entirely from the temporal structure of trajectory-derived kinematic features, making the approach applicable across a broad range of operational environments and vessel configurations. A confidence-weighted aggregation scheme further improves trajectory-level prediction robustness by down-weighting ambiguous temporal windows and amplifying high-confidence predictions. The method is validated across four candidate motion models under diverse simulated maneuver conditions.

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. 
Section~\ref{sec:related} reviews related work on motion model identification, ship dynamics, and trajectory-based classification. 
Section~\ref{sec:method} presents the 
proposed motion model classification framework, encompassing the problem 
formulation, dynamics-oriented feature extraction pipeline, TCN encoder 
architecture, joint training objective, and confidence-weighted 
trajectory-level inference scheme.
Section~\ref{sec:results} reports experimental results and comparative analysis. 
Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes with directions for future work.

\section{Literature review}
\label{sec:related}

Accurate kinematic and dynamic modeling of marine vessels has been a 
central concern in naval architecture and marine control systems for 
several decades. The Nomoto model, introduced in its first- and 
second-order forms, remains one of the most widely adopted 
representations for describing the yaw dynamics of surface ships under 
helm input~\cite{nomoto1957}. More comprehensive representations, 
including the three-degree-of-freedom maneuvering models formulated by 
Fossen, account for coupled surge, sway, and yaw dynamics and have 
become standard references in marine control literature 
~\cite{fossen2011handbook}. Bicycle kinematic and unicycle models, 
originally developed for wheeled mobile robots, have also found 
application in USV guidance owing to their computational simplicity and 
suitability for low-speed maneuvering scenarios~\cite{campion1996structural}. 
Despite the availability of these well-established model families, 
determining which model best governs a specific deployed vessel remains 
a largely unresolved problem in practice.

Classical system identification approaches address this through dedicated 
sea trials and regression-based parameter fitting to hydrodynamic 
databases~\cite{ljung1999system, perez2002ship}. More recent efforts have 
explored recursive least squares and extended Kalman filter formulations 
for online parameter estimation~\cite{zhang2017recursive}, as well as 
grey-box methods that blend physical structure with data-driven parameter 
learning~\cite{xue2021greybox}. While effective within their respective 
settings, all of these approaches presuppose knowledge of the governing 
model structure and require either explicit control input measurements or 
dedicated onboard sensing hardware. This limits their applicability in 
scenarios where only pose observations of the vessel are available and 
the underlying model class itself is unknown.

The emergence of machine learning has opened alternative avenues for 
identifying dynamical systems directly from state trajectory data. 
Sparse identification of nonlinear dynamics (SINDy) demonstrated that 
governing equations can be recovered from trajectory observations via 
sparse regression over candidate function libraries~\cite{brunton2016sindy}, 
though such symbolic approaches are sensitive to noise and do not 
naturally extend to classification among a discrete set of candidate 
models. In the robotics domain, Sebastian and Ben-Tzvi showed that 
terrain type can be inferred from the pose evolution of a ground robot 
under known control inputs using a support vector machine, establishing 
that motion response signatures encode sufficient information for system 
discrimination without dedicated sensing~\cite{sebastian2019terrain}. 
Analogous ideas have been explored in fault detection and structural 
health monitoring, where convolutional and recurrent architectures have 
been applied to classify dynamical behavior from time-series 
measurements~\cite{zhao2019convolutional}. These works collectively 
support the hypothesis that trajectory observations alone can 
discriminate among distinct motion model classes, provided the feature 
representation is designed to capture intrinsic dynamic signatures rather 
than superficial path geometry.

For sequential and time-series data, recurrent architectures such as 
Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks have been widely adopted owing 
to their capacity to model long-range temporal 
dependencies~\cite{hochreiter1997lstm}. However, LSTMs suffer from 
vanishing gradients over long sequences and are inherently sequential in 
computation, which limits training efficiency. Temporal Convolutional 
Networks (TCNs), introduced by Bai et al., address these shortcomings 
through dilated causal convolutions with residual connections, achieving 
large receptive fields while remaining fully parallelizable 
~\cite{bai2018empirical}. TCNs have demonstrated competitive or superior 
performance relative to recurrent architectures across sequence modeling 
benchmarks and have been applied to trajectory prediction 
~\cite{nikhil2018convolutional} and motion classification 
tasks~\cite{lea2017temporal}, making them a natural candidate for 
encoding the multi-scale temporal structure of vessel maneuver dynamics.

Beyond supervised classification, contrastive learning has emerged as a 
powerful paradigm for learning structured embedding spaces that generalize 
across distributional variations. Self-supervised frameworks such as 
SimCLR and MoCo learn representations by contrasting augmented views of 
the same sample~\cite{chen2020simclr, he2020moco}, while supervised 
contrastive learning, proposed by Khosla et al., extends this to the 
fully labeled setting by treating all same-class samples as positives, 
enforcing simultaneous intra-class compactness and inter-class 
separation~\cite{khosla2020supervised}. In the time-series domain, 
contrastive objectives have been applied to learn invariant 
representations across sensor modalities~\cite{eldele2021time}, 
demonstrating robustness to input variation that is directly relevant 
to the maneuver diversity encountered in vessel trajectory data.

Taken together, the reviewed literature reveals a clear and unaddressed 
gap: while marine motion models are well-characterized and data-driven 
sequence classifiers have matured considerably, no prior work has 
formulated the identification of a vessel's governing kinematic model 
as a trajectory-level classification problem solvable from pose 
observations alone. Furthermore, the combination of TCN-based temporal 
encoding with supervised contrastive learning for motion model 
discrimination in the maritime domain has not been previously explored. 
This work directly addresses both gaps by proposing a unified framework 
that derives dynamics-oriented kinematic features from raw pose 
trajectories and trains a TCN encoder under a joint contrastive and 
cross-entropy objective to classify the ego ship's motion model without 
access to control inputs, onboard sensors, or prior model structure 
assumptions.
